==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*midja-'', from Indo-European ''*medhyo-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[midde]], Old Saxon [[middi]] (Dutch [[mits]]), Old High German [[mitti]] (German [[mitt]]), Old Norse [[miðr]] (Swedish [[midja]]), Gothic [[𐌼𐌹𐌳𐌾𐌹𐍃]].  The IE root is also the source of Latin [[medius]], Greek [[μεσος]], Russian [[межа]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /mɪdd/

===Adjective===
''*'''''midd''' ''(only attested in oblique forms)''
# pertaining to the [[middle]] or [[centre]] of something, especially of periods of time
#:''Þeah ic nu gange on midde þa sceade deaðes ne ondræde ic me nan yfel'': though I now walk amidst the shadow of death I fear no evil.  (King Alfred, Psalm 22)

